\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Here is a checklist of steps we used to test this mode}
\par 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033 {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 1. Ensure that the telescope is VERY well polar aligned}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 2. Switch off the telescope drive}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 3. Point the telescope at the celestial equator (DEC=00:00:00)}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 4. Use short normal mode exposures (~1 minute) to observe the }
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    \tab direction of drift}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 5. Align the ccd camera so that the stars drift down the ccd in perfect}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    \tab alignment with the ccd columns}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 6. If possible, calculate the appropriate per-row drift delay using the}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    \tab fratio, sidereal rate, and ccd pixel scale  (good luck!)}
\par 
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 7. Otherwise, take short drift-scan exposures (~500 rows) and}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    \tab step through a set of different drift delays. As a guide, we found the}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    \tab optimal equatorial drift delay to be 344000 microseconds using a}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    \tab 8" F/6 scope with an Ap7p camera.}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 8. Plot the drift-delays vs length-of-star-trails}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 9. Determine the zero point drift-delay}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 10. Enter the optimal delay into the drift-scan GUI.}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 11. Take a short, and then long drift-scan to verify.}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 12. Move to a different DEC position}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 13. Click "Calculate duration and per-line rate in microsecs"}
