\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 There are three methods for using the software via a remote computer.}
\par 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\b 1.}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls4\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\b {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b Standard X-windows}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi0\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi0\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033 {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Use the standard X-windows display redirection facility to point}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033 {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0     the display to another computer (named "other" for example).}
\par 
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 \tab eg. {\b setenv DISPLAY other:0}}
\par 
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    The "{\b xhost +ccd-name}" command must also be issued on the "other"}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    computer, to allow remote displays to take place (where ccd-name is the}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    name of the camera control computer).}
\par 
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    Finally , start the GUI as usual, the windows should appear on the}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    "other" machine.}
\par 
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    This method only works if both computer are running a *nix type operating}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0    system. X-windows is available for MS Windows, but it is usually expensive.}
\par 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\b {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b 2. VNC}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033 
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Use the VNC (Virtual network computing) software (which is free, and open-source).}
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 This package supports the remote viewing on the ccd GUI desktop on  *nix, windows, and Mac platforms. Even better, multiple remote users can simultaneously view the same dekstop, and even share interaction rights with the applications. Given fast network c
onnections (fast ethernet) this is a near optimal solution. The VNC package is just one of the items in the bundle of extras included in the cdrom version of the Linux Apogee Drivers cd, available from The Random Factory.}
\par 
\par {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Future releases of the driver will also include support for true client/server use of cameras. In this situation, the GUI will actually run on the remote machine, and only the low level camera access code will run on the camera controller computer.}
\par 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\b 3.}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls3\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\afs24\langfe255\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\b {\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b Client/Server}
